	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Early morning Gordon Infobits</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=145838" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/046918.html">Experience loss for thought???</a><P>

Verant: Considering the steep experience curve and the very real chance of losing your corpse for post 50 players<P>

<B>Well I wouldn't call it a "very real chance", I'd call it a non-negligible chance. Given sufficiently talented, knowledgeable, and powerful compatriots, it probably won't be an issue. The posts about this over the past few weeks have just been to remind people that the possibility does exist, as it has always existed, even though the skill of players up to this point has often made that possibility trivial.</B><P>

My idea - - No experience penalty when you die if your 51+. That doesn't seem to unreasonable does it! Though it probably doesn't fit your Vision(TM) which is predicated upon slowing people's progress so they will have to pay your salaries for yet another month. All i want is 5 good reasons why this isn't a good idea (and that Vision(TM) crap doesn't cout).<P>

<B>I guess I should ask for 5 good reasons why there shouldn't be experience loss at 51 when there is at 50. The reasons for experience loss at 51+ are the same reason as there is experience loss at any other level excluding levels 1-5. We do allow players to mitigate this chance to a mere fraction of the game design by providing resurrection. Of course you need to make friends with other people in game to have this benefit, which I don't think is unreasonable.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047200.html">Isnt everquest supposed to be fun?</a><P>

How many ppl remember everquest is actually a game?<P>

<B>Of course that's the goal, but as "fun" is entirely subjective, with each person having their own idea of what "fun" is, we try to provide as many different definitions of "fun" as possible in game.<P>

There are certain ideas of "fun" that are incompatible with other ideas. For instance, some might think that it would be fun if they were provided with items, levels, skills, and abilities with little or no effort. While we think that some might think this is fun in the short term, we firmly believe that those things will be more fun, and fun for a longer period of time, if they are earned rather than given.<P> 

Much in the same fashion that sunny days aren't appreciated without the cloudy ones, the amount of fun in the game is related to other factors that some might consider aren't fun. For another real world analogy, I spent the last 8 years in Arizona. There, with over 300 days of sunshine per year, we learn to appreciate the cloudy ones.<P> 

EQ is very much like this. Without the rarety of items, the amount of fun that people have by acquiring items is reduced. Without some downtime, those non-stop periods of edge-of-the-chair excitement that everyone has experienced would not be as special. Without the difficulty of advancement, advancement would not be as special.<P> 

Fun remains subjective, and will be subjective for every game, especially in MMORPGs where the goal of the developer is to attract long-term subscribers. People will quit these games and go on to the next one when the fun that they get from playing it is no longer worth the things that are necessary for the fun to exist in the first place. Our goal of course is to make sure that it takes a long time for the average person to traverse that course.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047204.html">FunLove 4070 Virus: downloaded from Everquest!</a><P>

This message is being posted after having run anti-virus software scans 50+ times and formatting once. Now every time I attempt to log on to Everquest and download the patches, I automatically receive this virus.<P>

<B>It's not coming from us.<P>

If the game executable is being infected between downloading it and scanning it, the virus is probably memory resident on your system. <P>

Viruses of this type will usually cause you to download new executables each time you connect to the patch server as the patch program detects that there is something wrong with the one in your directory. <P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047236.html">Players being banned on a whim? Gordon please read</a><P>

This week I have seen numerous posts of people being banned for what seems to be either a misunderstanding or just a lack of communication.<P>

<B>Hello,<P>

To try and reassure you, we don't ban people on a whim, as it would make no sense for us to kick out paying customers without reason. <P>

People who are suspended or banned frequently come to this board to plead their case to the public. As a matter of personal and professional policy, I won't comment publicly on the specifics of any individual customer's account, but I do investigate each issue as they are presented here so that I can feel confident when I say what I said in the first paragraph. <P>

As I mentioned above, I can't come out here and defend these issues as they come up. It's not appropriate to address customer's private issues even if they choose to bring them out in the public light first. I will however be happy to address these issues with the account holder in email, or put their request into the hands of someone who can answer their questions. <P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/047247.html">SO, what is supposed ot be in the "emergency patch" patch?</a><P>

Any ideas? Any projections?<P>

<B>It's nothing game-effecting for most people, just a new eqgame.exe for to solve a frequent crashing issue being experienced by a few people.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
